+ {"ts": "2026-07-19T04:09:21.079Z", "seq": 32, "kind": "observation", "summary": "ROOT CAUSE: the eu7 harness CANNOT COMPLETE ON CPU on this box -- BATCH=256 exceeds its own hardcoded 600s drain timeout at the measured embed rate. Measured at 4ca70ba6 by bisecting N (three runs): n=7667 FAILED, n=200 FAILED, n=20 PASSED. All three failures are identical: panic at eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:414 'seed drain (batch): Scheduler' == engine.drain(600_000) -> wait_for_idle timed out -> EngineError::Scheduler. THE WORKER IS NOT WEDGED: n=20 passed cleanly (exit 0, vector_stage recall@10 = 1.0000, 258.54s) so the embed/projection path is FUNCTIONALLY CORRECT. It is THROUGHPUT. The n=20 run reports seed_ms=111670 for 20 docs = 0.179 docs/sec, which is ~7.3x SLOWER than the 1.3 docs/sec the harness docstring assumes (:97-99). At 0.179 docs/s a BATCH of 256 needs ~1430s, so it can NEVER drain inside the hardcoded 600_000 ms -- the harness is STRUCTURALLY unable to run here regardless of N, because failure happens on the FIRST batch. Full 7667-doc seed would need ~11.9 HOURS even if the timeout were raised. NOT a weights problem (cache complete: config.json + tokenizer.json + model.safetensors present) and not CPU contention (load 4.5 of 24 cores). OPTIONS for Slice 40: (a) reduce BATCH 256 -> 64 (64/0.179 = 358s, fits inside 600s) or make BATCH/timeout env-tunable -- minimal, surgical, does NOT change measurement semantics; (b) raise the drain timeout and accept a ~12h CPU run; (c) investigate the 7x throughput shortfall vs the documented rate, which may itself be a real CPU-embed regression worth catching. RECOMMEND (a)+(c). NOTE THE TENSION: TC-12 forbids running eu7 on GPU for comparability, and CPU cannot finish -- so R-20-EU7 has NO runnable path until this is fixed. Slice 40 must not treat this as optional. SIDE-EFFECT HAZARD: the harness WRITES dev/plans/runs/eu7-latest-measurements.json into the repo on every run, so a reduced-N scouting run silently produces a file that LOOKS authoritative (the n=20 run wrote recall=1.0000 there). Do not commit it from a scouting run.", "cx": "TC-19", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "40", "status": "OPEN", "refs": ["file:src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs", "seq:26"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-19T23:49:04.707Z", "seq": 33, "kind": "observation", "summary": "R-20-EU7 is CLOSED BY HITL (zero runs authorized) but the prohibition is UNENFORCEABLE: eu7_real_corpus_ac has no #[ignore] and no env gate, so a bare 'cargo test --workspace' or 'cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --features operator' WILL execute it. Slice 5 complied only by running targets individually. Per fix-the-tooling-not-the-actor this wants a mechanical guard -- but a naive #[ignore] creates the OPPOSITE hazard at Slice 40, where eu7 IS wanted and would then silently never run (TC-13 vacuous-green class). Needs a Steward/HITL decision on the guard's shape, not a unilateral fix.", "id": "TC-20", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:00b46b84"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-19T23:49:04.735Z", "seq": 34, "kind": "observation", "summary": "PRE-EXISTING (not 0.8.20): pr_g10_reranker_ce has NOT COMPILED under --features default-reranker since 0.8.19's SearchHit.id u64->IdSpace swap; file verified byte-identical to baseline, so this is not a Slice-5 regression. Root cause of its survival: the release DoD full-workspace gate (cargo clippy/check --workspace --all-targets) does NOT cover feature-gated targets, so default-reranker targets are invisible to it. Two gaps: fix the compile break, and decide whether the DoD gate must fan out over feature combinations.", "id": "TC-21", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:00b46b84"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-19T23:49:04.758Z", "seq": 35, "kind": "caveat", "summary": "STRUCTURAL: a BREAKING change to the write path cannot be X1-verified from an orchestration worktree. maturin develop / pip install -e are prohibited there (they rebind the shared .venv), so the Python native extension cannot be built or executed -- Slice 5c's SourceId newtype broke ~50 Python fixtures that could only be statically checked (py_compile + ruff + AST audit), never run. TypeScript is NOT subject to this: 'npm install' in src/ts is directory-local, creates no shared state, and gave a real tsc + node --test green (170 passing). Rule of thumb for future breaking slices: TS is worktree-verifiable, Python is NOT, and a main-tree pytest run is owed before land. 0.8.19 already taught that an env trap is a landing blocker, not a follow-up.", "id": "TC-22", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:875017a2"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-19T23:49:04.781Z", "seq": 36, "kind": "observation", "summary": "TOOLING: implementer closure output.json artifacts left UNTRACKED (orchestration.md section 8 permits this, orchestrator promotes later) are destroyed by routine git hygiene. Happened TWICE in Slice 5: one implementer ran 'git checkout --' on uncommitted lib.rs and lost a whole implementation; another ran 'git stash push -u' + 'git stash drop' and swept away three prior sub-slices' untracked output.json (recovered byte-identical from the dropped stash's third parent, verified via git hash-object). Fix the tooling: have implementers COMMIT output.json as their final commit rather than leaving it untracked, so the closure witness is not destructible by ordinary git commands.", "id": "TC-23", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open"}
++{"ts": "2026-07-19T23:49:04.804Z", "seq": 37, "kind": "caveat", "summary": "BEHAVIOR CHANGE to a shipped knob: enforce_provenance_retention's 'cap' now bounds SWEEPABLE rows, not physical rows in operational_mutations. Slice 5 exempts two collections from the sweep -- the erasure-audit collection (per HITL ruling 'there must be an auditable record of deletion event', defect D-A) and the new pending-redaction intent queue (sweeping it would re-create the P2 false-success defect via cap pressure). Consequence: an operator who sized 'cap' against physical row count will see the table grow beyond it by the exempt collections. Deliberate, but it needs a changelog line and any operator-facing retention docs updated.", "id": "TC-24", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:18197495"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-19T23:49:04.827Z", "seq": 38, "kind": "observation", "summary": "VACUOUS-GREEN HAZARD: src/rust/crates/fathomdb/tests/sdk_only_erasure.rs is '#![cfg(not(feature = \"operator\"))]' by design -- it proves an SDK-ONLY consumer with no CLI/operator surface can erase (R-20-E4). Consequence: any feature-unified run (cargo test --workspace, or anything enabling 'operator') compiles it to ZERO tests and reports success having asserted nothing. It requires the explicit invocation 'cargo test -p fathomdb --test sdk_only_erasure'. CI must carry that invocation explicitly or the R-20-E4 guarantee is untested.", "id": "TC-25", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:4b78658d"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-19T23:49:04.851Z", "seq": 39, "kind": "todo", "summary": "DESIGN TEXT CORRECTION OWED: plan-0.8.20 R-20-E8 and the v4/v5 designs state the legacy provenance backfill is gated on 'logical_id IS NULL ONLY', rationale being that governed rows stay purge-addressable by logical_id. codex section 9 proved that rationale is TRUE FOR NODES and FALSE FOR EDGES -- purge_inner resolves targets exclusively via 'SELECT state FROM canonical_nodes WHERE logical_id = ?1', so an edge's logical_id is only a supersession identity and confers NO purge-addressability. A legacy edge with source_id NULL and logical_id NOT NULL was therefore erasable by no verb at all. Shipped fix (step 21): nodes keep the logical_id IS NULL gate; edges backfill on source_id IS NULL alone. TC-11 pin NOT affected (only source_id is written, never logical_id). The design/plan prose still states the unqualified rule and must be corrected.", "id": "TC-26", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:989fd7ef"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T00:51:27.551Z", "seq": 40, "kind": "observation", "summary": "HARD-RULE TRAP: 'maturin develop' can fire AUTONOMOUSLY from a worktree without any agent issuing it. src/python/tests/conftest.py::_ensure_test_hooks_binding (line ~118) shells out to 'maturin develop' to build the test-hooks extension. So merely running the Python suite from an orchestration worktree attempts the one thing the build-isolation rule forbids (it rebinds the SHARED .venv). Observed live in Slice 5 fix-3. It failed harmlessly ONLY because the interpreter was not an activated virtualenv (conftest guards on that); with an activated venv it would have rebound the shared .venv to the worktree. Orchestrator verified no damage: /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/.venv/.../fathomdb.pth mtime still 2026-07-09, still pointing at the MAIN repo. Per fix-the-tooling-not-the-actor, conftest needs an explicit guard that refuses to run maturin when CWD is a linked worktree.", "id": "TC-27", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:8e09b950"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T00:51:27.581Z", "seq": 41, "kind": "observation", "summary": "UPDATE (raised on THREE consecutive codex rounds in Slice 5): the eu7 no-run prohibition is still unenforceable, and scripts/agent-test.sh contains a bare 'cargo test --workspace' that WOULD execute eu7_real_corpus_ac. Slice 5 complied only by every implementer remembering to pass '-- --skip eu7_real_corpus_ac_validation' or to run targets individually. Original entry stands: the guard's shape needs a Steward/HITL decision because a naive #[ignore] creates the opposite (vacuous-green) hazard at Slice 40 where eu7 IS wanted.", "id": "TC-20", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:8e09b950"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T00:51:27.604Z", "seq": 42, "kind": "caveat", "summary": "DESIGN HARDENING OWED (FU-FIX3-3): the pending-redaction queue introduced in Slice 5 is a transactional outbox stored as ordinary operational_mutations rows (collection_name='erasure_pending_redaction'). Its 'a row is removed ONLY when the obligation is discharged' invariant is upheld by THREE separate correct call sites (retention sweep exemption, excise_collection_record refusal, the NotFound arm) rather than enforced structurally -- and it shipped with three ways to remove a row of which only one proved anything. Every known path is now closed, but NOTHING PREVENTS A FIFTH. Codex found a defect in this mechanism on each of rounds 1, 2 and 3. Structural options: give it its own table with no generic DELETE verb, or a trigger. Deliberately NOT done inside a fix round.", "id": "TC-28", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:8e09b950"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T00:51:27.627Z", "seq": 43, "kind": "observation", "summary": "RESIDUAL PATTERN (FU-FIX2-2): 'freeze the projection scanner, then wait on a DATABASE-derived idleness probe' is the shape behind a Slice-5 P2 where erase_source/excise_source could strand unqueued work and time out with EngineError::Scheduler after the full 30s LIFECYCLE_DRAIN_TIMEOUT_MS. purge and (now) the source-erasure path drain BEFORE freezing. run_rebuild is the LAST remaining instance that still freezes before its only drain -- likely benign (operator action, not a write-then-act sequence) but unaudited. Also logged: operator_cli::t_s34_dump_mutations_lock_held_exits_71 is FLAKY under cross-binary lock contention (it spawns its own lock holder); 25/25 in isolation, flaked once in a full-suite run. Touches no erasure path.", "id": "TC-29", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:7be20ec3"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T01:09:57.581Z", "seq": 44, "kind": "observation", "summary": "VACUOUS-GREEN HAZARD (found closing Slice 5): scripts/agent-lint-md.sh exits 0 SILENTLY from any linked worktree because node_modules/.bin/markdownlint-cli2 is absent there and the structural lint self-skips -- same failure class as TC-13 (eu7 corpus skip) and TC-25 (cfg-gated target compiles to zero tests). Running the real linter (npx --yes markdownlint-cli2) gives exit 1: 9 PRE-EXISTING MD025/MD001 issues in dev/research/personal-agent-database-market-2026-07-02.md, untouched since c366d6e0 (2026-07-02). Two implications: (a) the markdown gate is unreliable from every orchestration worktree, and (b) agent-lint-md.sh is likely RED in the main tree right now on that research file, independent of 0.8.20. Note also STATUS boards sit inside the config's dev/plans/runs/** ignore and are never linted.", "id": "TC-30", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open"}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T02:14:53.190Z", "seq": 45, "kind": "observation", "summary": "WRITE/READ PROVENANCE ASYMMETRY -- the 'NO SDK EXPOSURE' erasure gap, now measured. 0.8.20 makes provenance structurally MANDATORY on write (SourceId newtype), but PySearchHit.source_id is populated ONLY for graph-arm hits and is None for every two-arm (text/vector) hit -- documented at src/rust/crates/fathomdb-py/src/lib.rs:537-539. So a caller can be forced to supply provenance yet cannot read it back on an ordinary search hit. Measured consequence: BOTH remaining Python suite failures (test_option2_elps_pipeline::test_build_fathomdb_elps_path_uses_ingest_with_extractor and test_verify_embed_db::test_complete_embed_is_queryable) are caused by this -- _doc_id_of falls through the 'if sid:' branch because source_id is None, reaching int(sh.id) which has raised TypeError since 0.8.19 made SearchHit.id an IdSpace (C-2). ONE read-side fix (expose source_id on all arms) likely closes BOTH. Verified pre-existing: identical failures on origin/main f22e4947 in an isolated A/B clone; _doc_id_of is byte-identical on main.", "id": "TC-31", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:9c87d758"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T02:14:53.219Z", "seq": 46, "kind": "observation", "summary": "ERASURE GAP adjacent to R-20-E2 (found during fix-4, NOT fixed -- entity-identity design, out of slice scope): ingest_with_extractor dedupes entities within a batch by logical_id derived from (kind, name). Two documents naming the SAME entity collapse to ONE canonical row carrying the FIRST document's provenance. Consequence for erasure completeness: erasing the second document leaves that entity row behind, still attributed to the first document -- the row survives an erasure that should have removed the second document's contribution. Visible in the ELPS stub path (both docs yield 'TestEntity' => 1 node). Interacts with the multi-doc per-entity attribution contract added in 0.8.20: attribution is now required per entity, but dedup silently discards all but the first attribution.", "id": "TC-32", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:9c87d758"]}
++{"ts": "2026-07-20T02:14:53.242Z", "seq": 47, "kind": "observation", "summary": "UPDATE -- GUARD SHIPPED, and the hazard was confirmed LIVE not hypothetical. src/python/tests/conftest.py now REFUSES to shell out to 'maturin develop' unless FATHOMDB_TESTS_ALLOW_REBUILD=1 is set (0.8.20 Slice 5, commit 265c54c0). During verification the probe showed the orchestration worktree's binding LACKS test-hooks, meaning the pre-guard code WOULD have rebuilt from that worktree into the shared .venv given an activated virtualenv. Downstream effect to know about: scripts/agent-test.sh's pytest step now FAILS LOUDLY instead of silently auto-rebuilding -- any isolated/throwaway verification environment must set FATHOMDB_TESTS_ALLOW_REBUILD=1 explicitly (the fresh-clone verification run did exactly this).", "id": "TC-27", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:265c54c0"]}
